Ah — you’re referring to coprophagy, which rabbits do as a normal biological process.

Rabbits produce two kinds of droppings:
	1.	Hard pellets – the dry ones people usually see.
	2.	Cecotropes – softer nutrient-rich pellets produced in the cecum (part of their gut).

Rabbits eat the cecotropes directly after they’re produced. It’s not random behavior — it’s part of their digestion system. Plant material is hard to break down the first time through, so the first pass lets microbes process the food, and the second pass lets the rabbit absorb nutrients like:
	•	B vitamins
	•	vitamin K
	•	amino acids
	•	short-chain fatty acids

So biologically it’s a two-pass digestion system.

